issue.title: Logic Constraints

milestone.title: v2.2 Release
milestone.description: This release focuses on verifying your container doesn't have any errors that can be caught with static analysis.

issue.body: Annotated Container has the capacity to analyze your annotations and tell you when there might be something wrong, they're called _logical constraints_. Though this system is not well-documented at the moment, you can find relevant code in the `Cspray\AnnotatedContainer\LogicalConstraint` namespace. This document is intended to act as a long-running list for the types of logical constraints that have been accounted for, are planned to account for, or are intentionally not going to account for. A future phase of the project will involve implementing the logical constraints listed here. Constraints are categorized by their type. The current constraint types are: - **Notice** These might indicate something is wrong but could be handled at runtime - **Warning** There is a large probability that this constraint violation will result in some error - **Critical** It is all but certain that attempting to use the code in this configuration will result in an error. ## Accounted For Constraints - [x] If an abstract service does not have any concrete services defined for it. _Warning_ - [x] If an abstract service has more than 1 alias defined for it. _Notice_ ## Planned to Account For Constraints While this is intended to be an exhaustive list it might be possible that conditions exist the author has not considered. If you believe that there's a violation missing in this list of constraints please comment below. ### Critical - [ ] If you duplicate the name of a `#[Service]`. - [ ] If you annotate a class method with `#[ServiceDelegate]` that has private or protected visibility. - [ ] If you annotate a class method with `#[ServicePrepare]` that has private or protected visibility. - [ ] Possible to repeat Attributes that should not be repeatable. Now that you can have your own Attributes you could potentially mark the same service with multiple implementations of ServiceAttribute. This would undoubtedly cause a slew of problems as definitions would likely be duplicated. - [ ] If multiple concrete services are marked primary for the same abstract service. ### Warning - [ ] If you annotate a distinct method parameter or property with multiple `#[Inject]` Attributes that do not specify a unique set of profiles. - [ ] If there are multiple concrete aliases for the same abstract service that are marked as primary. - [ ] If you Attribute a class to be created with a #[ServiceDelegate] that has not also been marked as a #[Service] ### Notice ## Intentionally Will-Not-Fix _No known logical constraints will be ignored._
